[Dr. Karesh is Co-chair of the IUCN Species Survival Commission - Veterinary
Specialist Group. For more information on the WCS Field Veterinary Program, go
to <http://www.fieldvet.org>; for more information on the IUCN SSC Veterinary
Specialist Group, go to <http://www.iucn-vsg.org>.
ProMED-mail welcomes the opportunity to relay this information on the current
activities of the Field Veterinary program of the Wildlife Conservation
Society in Republic of Congo. Circumstantial evidence supports the current
belief that Ebola virus reaches the human population as a result of the
hunting, slaughter, and consumption of non-human primates and perhaps other
wild mammals, which themselves may succumb to the infection. The primary
reservoir of Ebola virus has remained elusive, and the virus may be maintained
in a species which does not exhibit signs and symptoms of disease. We invite
Dr. Karesh to keep us updated on the progress of the field work. - Mod.CP]
[In 1999 I presented a poster at the annual meeting of the American Society of
Tropical Medicine & Hygiene entitled "Marburg Virus: the Search for the
Source." With its large photo of a charging African elephant it provoked much
mirth among participants. I gave the following reasons for suspecting the
elephant: pygmies are the tribe with the highest filovirus antibody rate in
the Congo; they traditionally hunt elephants; they poke around in elephant
feces to determine how warm the trail is; and 2 fatal cases of Marburg virus
infection were linked to Kitum Cave, in Kenya, which is so big elephants have
been seen inside, carving chunks of mineral-rich rock out with their tusks --
see photos in: http://www.richardpreston.net/guide/hz/download.html ; and
among the thousands of animal species collected and tested in the USA from
around that cave (all negative), none were elephants.
Marburg is the only other virus, with Ebola virus, in the family Filoviridae,
so they might have similar sources. We wish the investigators success in
their collection of mammalian & fecal specimens. - Mod.JW]
